 <h2>
  <span class="mw-headline">
   The Disease
  </span>
 </h2>
 <p>
  <i>
   Staphylococcus aureus
  </i>
  is an important nosocomial and community-acquired pathogen.
  <i>
   S. aureus
  </i>
  is the most common cause of hospital acquired infection, causing clinical disease in 2% of all patient admissions in the UK. Not only does it cause enormous numbers of infections, but
  <i>
   S. aureus
  </i>
  in hospitals are becoming increasingly resistant to antibiotics. In several industrialised nations including parts of Europe, the US and Japan, 40-60&nbsp;% of all hospital
  <i>
   S. aureus
  </i>
  are now resistant to methicillin (methicillin-resistant
  <i>
   Staphylococcus aureus
  </i>
  , MRSA).
 </p>
 <p>
  TW20 is a representative of a highly transmissible MRSA outbreak that occurred on an intensive care unit in a large London hospital. The strain has been typed as sequence type (ST)239 by MLST.
 </p>
 <a name="The_Genome">
 </a>
 <h2>
  <span class="mw-headline">
   The Genome
  </span>
 </h2>
 <p>
  The
  <i>
   S. aureus
  </i>
  strain TW20 genome is composed of a single circular chromosome of  3,075,806 bp and two plasmids (pTW20_1 and pTW20_2) of 29,585 bp and 3,011 bp, and was sequenced in collaboration with with Dr. Jonathan Edgeworth, Dept. of Infection,
  <a href="http://www.guysandstthomas.nhs.uk/home.aspx" class="external text" title="http://www.guysandstthomas.nhs.uk/home.aspx" rel="nofollow">
   Guy's and St Thomas' Hospital
  </a>
  , London and Dr. Jodi Lindsay, Centre for Infection &amp; Molecular Medicine,
  <a href="http://www.sgul.ac.uk/" class="external text" title="http://www.sgul.ac.uk/" rel="nofollow">
   St George's Medical School
  </a>
  , London.
 </p>
